</center></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#4D4D4D><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/ucaledhontelrana.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Caledhon TelRana</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>l33t board camper</span><br>  Posts: 152<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(6/7/02 9:38:20 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: With all of the topics sharing this theme:</span><hr size=1> God would not send someone to hell merely because they are gay.  If a Christian decides, for whatever reason, to get it on with another guy (or girl), then he's still going to Heaven regardless.  Note that this is a Protestant belief - I'm not really sure what the Catholic/Anglican position is.  However, we (Protestants in general) believe that once you accept Jesus and truly believe, then nothing can ever separate you from that moment.  Lapses, evil deeds, nothing... it's all paid for.  So no, being gay won't damn you to Hell for eternity.  Having gay sex would just be one more in a long list of all the sins that everyone has committed, any and all of which are sufficient to damn you, except for Jesus' intervention.<br>
<br>
Of course, it's not quite that simple.  Then you get to the popular theory of &quot;Ok, I'll say the words and talk to a preacher for an hour, then go do whatever the hell I want, because I'm set!  I can't lose my ticket to Heaven!&quot;  Well... no.  Because if you think like this, you don't really believe in Jesus and everything he teaches and stands for, because if you did then you would actually care about His word, his commands, etc.  Therefore, having gay sex might be a lapse... like adultery would for a straight person... everyone is tempted, some by different things.  Everyone gives in to temptation occasionally.  But someone who convinces themselves that being gay and continually having gay sex is OK with God and consistent with being a Christian is fooling themself terribly.  Whether they are truly a Christian or not, only they know... odds are, they aren't, because someone who truly is would care about the issue enough to find out what God's will is, and then follow it.<br>
<br>
The issue is much deeper than most people here seem to think.  Can a gay person be a Christian?  Certainly... but if they were *truly* a Christian, with heartfelt honest belief in Jesus and the Bible, then rather than attempting to justifying themselves, they would do their best to repress the homosexual urges they feel, and not act upon them.  The same way that a straight Christian would attempt to block out thoughts of adultery and hopefully not act on them.<br>
<br>
The base issue is that of true, heartfelt belief.  The problem - how to detect such belief?  How do you know it is present?  Answer:  Actions. <p>Caledhon TelRana - 53 Warrior<br><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=51701">
