<br>
Of course now that the majority of those of the Christian faith follow the New Testiment (not to the letter, will get into that later) because over the last two thousand years, the human society have, shall we say, out grown, the simple idealistics of the Old Testiment. In fact, many today would argue many things listed under the Old Testiment were in fact barbaric.<br>
<br>
Interesting notion, eh? Part of the Bible, a holy text of a religion, is considered barbaric. I would go into detail, but I'm sure many before me have found some things said in the Old Testiment hard to swollow as a civilized person. The point of the matter is, the human society developed, both in understanding of the world around them, and in understanding of each other. As a result, new laws, and new expectations must be created in order to keep up with our expasion of thought. Hence the reason why the New Testiment was the &quot;rule book&quot; since, say, the 12th century.<br>
<br>
Now that we are in the 21st century, the inadiquisies of the New Testiment have long since became apparent. It no longer fit our lifestyle, and our way of thinking, to blindly follow a preacher and his interpretation of a book. Instead, in our society we encourage free thinking, to interpret what we ready by our own understanding, which, the human ego dictates as vastly superior to many around us.<br>
<br>
The Age of Reason have come and past. Today is an age of, I donno, Individuality? We all read the &quot;holy texts&quot; and come up with our own interpretations, deciding whether we want to follow, and what we don't want to follow. In fact, we point our fingers and laugh at those religions whom the clergy withold all power of interpretation. (The current middle eastern crisis comes to mind) We have out grown the &quot;laws&quot; and &quot;rules&quot; in the Old Testiment almost entirely.  We are almost to the point of out growing the New Testiment, as evident by the more and more abstract interpretations of the Bible you hear from clergy today.<br>
<br>
By reading, and interpreting the Bible, or any other holy texts as an individual, it is likely we develop unique understandings of what we read. Therefore, instead of having one preacher giving his interpretation to 300 odd individuals, we now have 301 versions of interpretations. As our society changes, our individualism may have a profound effect on the organization of religion. Instead of going to church, we can just read the Bible ourselves and see what we can get from it. In fact, if you look at the percentage of people who went to Church 800 years ago, and compare it to today, I think there's probably a huge decline. <br>
<br>
Yes, the Christian faith have changed over the years, as the society of their followers change. Gone are the days when no one worked on Sundays. Gone are the days when there was only one demonimation. Gone are the days when preachers could make people to go church by talking about the punishments. The Christian God has been protrayed as forgiving to vengful, from all-caring to almost to aloof, from all-forgiving to knit  picking to the point of annoyance. Throughout the ages, preachers have used their influence an interpreted the Bible according to their needs. Now, the individuals do the same.<br>
<br>
How many years will it take for us to out grow the New Testiment? How many years before we only follow the core values of the Bible, which is essentially the same as the core values of half a dozen religions and fully a dozen philosophies?<br>
