The point of the matter is, religion is based on faith, and faith does not, and cannot be proved in a logical mannor. In fact, to have faith is to belief against all odds, therefore it is extremely difficult to convince someone who has faith to change their views. Call it blind faith, thick-headedness, stubborness, having their heads up their asses, or truly devout. As long as one has faith, then I suppose whatever gods they follow is happy.<br>
<br>
However, that these faithy often fails to understand is that since faith has nothing to do with logic or reason, it is impossible to prove your faith to someone who doesn't have this particular faith. Trying to use reason and logic to prove the existance of any god is nothing more than wasted effort. <br>
Therefore, I find it *extremely* amusing when members of one faith accuse members of another faith of being &quot;wrong&quot;. I always wanted to ask the particularly ensuthiastic to prove why their faith is &quot;better&quot; than someone else's faith. <br>
<br>
I do this just to see if they are stupid enough to fall into the logical trap. When they start to jabber and start quoting from their &quot;holy text&quot;, you've got them. They are now attempting to prove something that cannot be proven, which gives you a hint of how much understanding they have of their own religion, of their own faith. Nine for ensuthiasm. Negative several thousand for understanding.<br>
<br>
In my opinion, the ultimate goal of most religions that survives to date is simply there as a way of conduct for a person to get along better with those around him. The core of a religion is simply a set of values that the members of the faith should follow. Unfortunately, it seems the human society, with its politics and greed, corrupts religions faster than they could &quot;save&quot; the world. <p><BR>
