<br>
I can provide you with non-biblical, non-Christian texts that mention the existance of Jesus.  Approximately 150 years after his death, there was a large Jewish movement that suggested that Jesus was a sorceror - both admitting his existance and leading to the thought that he performed Miracles, but instead through sorcery.<br>
<br>
Do you believed Alexander the Great existed?  The first known documentary addressing his existance appeared approximately 200 years after his death, and you accept he exists.  The first written references we have from the bible are dated around 55 AD, 22 years after the alleged Death of Christ.<br>
<br>
Please list one historical document that is more valid than the bible.  Over 24000 historical bibles exist in different languages.  There are over 100000 discrepancies between these copies.  If you are to check what the discrepancies are, in most cases it's either spelling, or sentence structure.  Sentence Structure to any document written in Greek is pointless.  In English, saying &quot;I fed my dog&quot; and &quot;My dog fed me&quot; are totally different, but in Greek there is a definate word that is the subject of any sentence, therefore you could write the same thought of me feeding my dog many times over, different ways, and have the same meaning.<br>
<br>
The only book that comes close to having the number of historical copies and references and validity as a historic document is the Illiad, which has approximately 1/100'th the number of historical copies that the Bible does.  The earliest known copy of a Gospel is on a piece of papyrus found listing some of the quotes from the Book of John.  In Egyptian cultures (the language that it was written in) the style of writing changed dramatically depending on who ruled Egypt at the time.  The date of the writing on this papyrus is placed at between 98 and 150 AD, which would mean that we have proof of at least one copy existing as early as 55 years after the death of Christ.<br>
<br>
Even the most devout of Athiests or Agnostics will admit that Jesus existed.  Whether or not he was Christ is not going to be proven by any amount of factual basis that anyone will accept as being true.  But you have to be pretty unifnformed to argue that he never existed at all.<br>
<br>
If you would like, I can provide solid factual proof of most of the events of the bible.  I'll grant you that I can't find proof of a single miracle, other than suggestive texts that show that there was an eclypse in the middle of the day on the day Jesus was crucified.  But I can show you where historians have challenged it and later found it to be accurate.  I can provide you with many non-biblical references to the existance of Jesus and his death.  If you want me to, say the word.<br>
<br>
It's incredibly uninformed to say that he never existed.  I consider it debatable as to whether or not he is God.  But basically, what you are doing is akin to jumping into a discussion of whether the earth circles around the sun or vice versa, and trying to say there is no sun.<br>
<br>
