<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Homosexuality may be a sin according to the Old Testament, but then again so is looking at anyone with a 'lustful' eye. Or for that matter, not being a virgin at the time of your wedding.<br>
<br>
I think too many Christians buy into the hype and hysteria of TBN and what their pastors say. People have been raised not to think or try to make their own judgment calls on their faith. If Pastor Rod says homosexuality is wrong, by darn it has to be!! <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
A few things.  Homosexuality is a sin according to the New Testament as well, and looking at someone with a &quot;lustful eye&quot; isn't defined as a sin until the New Testament either.  Before that it was actions that defined sin and not thoughts, it was the reform Jesus attempted to bring to the Jewish church that taught that thoughts and intentions were sins too.<br>
<br>
If Pastor Rod told me that eating cheese was wrong, I'd go look it up and see if it were wrong with biblical references.  I'm a stickler, anything anyone tells me about the bible, I immediately demand quotes to back this theory.  ESPECIALLY if they are a Christian.<br>
<br>
Like earlier, someone mentioned Moses dropping 10 of the 20 stone tablet commandments he brought down from the mountain.  This was in a Mel Brooks Movie, and not anywhere in the bible.  I went and researched it because I didn't remember it, and I wanted to have a good standpoint for saying that it was not biblically sound.<br>
<br>
I don't have time to go through the gospels right now as I'm on my way to work, but I can tell you that 1st Timothy 1:10 address homosexuality, I can do more research later if you'd like.<br>
<br>
I do believe homosexuality is wrong, in the same way that I believe that stealing, murder, and not honoring your mother and father are wrong.  I don't believe in levels of sin - in fact, Jesus speaking of the Golden rules was in direct response to people asking someone to provide a heirarchy of sin.  Any Sin in sin, there is not first degree or second degree sin.  Therefore, while I believe homosexuality is wrong, I believe that we are all sinners.  I believe that if you are going to remove Homosexuals from your church, why stop at that sin?  Throw out anyone else who commits sin on a daily basis, and see what an eventful church service you have.<br>
<br>
Mulberry, you make some very blanket statements about Churches that seem to be based more off of propoganda than fact.  In the church I attend, I often pull aside my teacher and ask him to provide biblical references for anything I think is suspect.  I often privately call him on inconsistancies where he is teaching, or things I think are not right.  He doesn't say &quot;Holdan, leave here and don't come again,&quot; instead, he respects me for not taking everything he says at face value.  To suggest that all priests are liars and all churches are corrupt is simply wrong.  My church accepts donations, a small basket is passed around while people are praying - the intent is that if you don't want to give money, you don't feel peer pressured into it as no one is looking at you.  And they never mention you duty to give.  Instead, in the pamphlet they put out each week, they explain what percentage of donations go where, and what specifically those were spent on.  In essence, they provide us with simplified accounting books each week.<br>
<br>
I find your statements and demeanor a bit too blanket for things going on.  I personally dislike Christians who flame homosexuals, because it's pretty clear that we have already had our Last Righteous Judge.  I don't believe it's my place to judge individuals.  So while I say &quot;Hrm homosexuality is wrong&quot; in the same way I say &quot;Stealing is wrong&quot; I don't declare PEOPLE as wrong, or try to preach to them to change.  In fact, I don't preach to anyone to convert religions.  The only people I will dig into with biblical references for the point of altering them are people who claim to be Christians but show actions EXACTLY OPPOSITE of being a Christian.  Sin isn't exactly opposite of being a Christian, before we go down that road.<br>
<br>
I haven't mentioned them much but here are my beliefs:<br>
1.  God doesn't list proof for his existance out of respect for Free Will.  If God woke everyone up every morning as an alarm clock, we would have no will to accept or deny fellowship with him - we'd be ignorant to not accept it.<br>
<br>
2.  The Big Bang and evolution did occur, but they are not contrary to Biblical references.  I believe that evolution did occur because of Intelligent Design of creatures and the universe, and a guiding hand in the process.  While the bible says God created all life, I can create art with paint and a canvas, I don't have to magically conjure the materials to create it.<br>
<br>
3.  I believe in most Christian truths, I'm not going to list them because it will sound like preaching, and I don't preach or convert people.<br>
<br>
4.  I believe science provides examples both for the existance and non-existance of God.  I believe this is how God intended it.  If he could be proven, then again, we lose free will.<br>
<br>
5.  I believe in the existance of Hell, but not with literal Flames and suffering.  These were figures of speech.  I believe hell exists as an existance forever seperate of God, and that is the torture.  I don't believe in rivers of Lava and Flame, but instead believe these were illustrations to describe how deep the suffering was going to be.<br>
<br>
I don't think any of my beliefs are superior to anyone else's.  I think mine are right because they are mine, and I wouldn't follow them if I didn't think it.  But I don't think that I have a right to say that mine are more valid or that you are wrong for HAVING other beliefs, because that is judging you as a person.  I think that anyone who judges you for being an Athiest or Agnostic is wrong.  I believe anyone who forces morals or their religion on you is wrong.  That's why I chose to merely debate the issues being brought forth on this.  As people continue to raise intelligent questions, I will adress them.  I also concede that some people claiming to be Christians have done more damage with things they've said in this thread than any of the Athiests or Agnostics have.  And I believe that occurs on a daily basis.  There is a bummper sticker that I myself have considered purchasing - it reads &quot;Jesus protect me from thy followers&quot;.  And I believe that we often damage our faith more than anyone with a lack of faith ever could.<br>
<br>
So yeah, I agree most churches do things that are wrong.  I myself don't claim to be better than anyone else for being a Christian.  I don't think I have a right to tell you what to believe, but if you approach me with questions I will address them in a concise and factual manner.  I don't argue the topic of &quot;If you had faith you'd know&quot; because that's a pointless argument.  If they had faith and would know, they obviously don't have faith and don't know.  So arguing it is pointless.<br>
<br>
I don't think I've offended anyone with what I've said, but I do hope on some level I've offended some Christians for bashing on things they have said here.  I will not hesitate to correct I Christian I think is behaving poorly.  In fact, I will blast them out of the water if I can find scriptural proof that what they are doing is not right.  But I don't do the same to athiests, as forcing my religion on them will only make them bitter to it.<br>
<br>
-Holdan (Rambling again, but I really don't want to go to work and if I type I don't have to think about it) <p><DIV style="position:relative; width=80%; filter:glow(color=3300FF)"><a style="font-weight:bold; color:#FFFFFF; text-decoration: none" href=http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=94628>Holdan DreamStealer</a></div>
<DIV style="position:relative; width=80%; filter:glow(color=666666)"><a style="font-weight:bold; color:#FFFFFF; text-decoration: none" href=http://companions.windsofstorm.net>(The Companions)</a></div>


</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#4D4D4D><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/uholdan.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Holdan</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 91<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(6/7/02 2:07:54 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: With all of the topics sharing this theme:</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I just found this quote to be amusing. Just because a book was popular, and was printed or copied a number of times, hardly makes it a &quot;valid historical document&quot;. You even used the Illiad as an example of a widely documented book, and do you honestly believe everything inside the Illiad was in fact the truth? <br>
<br>
Sorry, but basing the validity of the contents of a book on the number of historical copies in existance is ridiculous. If 4 million copies of Steven King books are still in existance in two thousand years, will it make whatever King wrote true?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The reason I listed the existance of the many copies is to prove the validity of the bible as existing closely to as it exists today.  Think of it this way -<br>
<br>
If one of your friends comes up to you and says Larry said you are smelly, you are probably not too likely to believe it if Larry is a good friend and you lack a ripe odor.<br>
<br>
But if 10000 people all come and say larry told you that you smell, you would start to believe that Larry indeed, did try to tell you that.<br>
<br>
It's the same way with assessing the validity of old texts.  If I have a copy of a copy of a copy of a copy of a statment made by someone, it's like the telephone game.  But when I have over 24000 ancient texts that all are nearly word for word exact translations of the same document, I begin to belive that what they listed of the document saying is correct.<br>
<br>
And I argue that the Illiad has far less copies of historical nature for a point.  If you are to look at the inconsistancies in the Illiad in these 300 copies, they are paramount.<br>
<br>
If the bible were subject to the telephone game being played throughout generations, of the 24000 copies we have things would be added or ommited from them.  They existed in different regions of the world in different texts.  If you are going to say that oral tradition and changes are present in the texts presented, then these concepts should be apparant in the texts found.  One from India should have Christ saying that Cows were sacred to get believers from that area to convert to Christianity more easily, and perhaps some in other cultures should have Christ saying that all who follow him willbe resurrected into another earthly life.  But the point is that they don't.<br>
<br>
The inconsistancy of the Telephone game is apparant in modern society.  But it's important to note that in Biblical times, paper and books were so expensive that Rabbi's had to memorize the entire Old Testament.  People had stellar memories.  I've seen this, as in High School we had a Masai warrior come on tour.  He would take questions from the crowd for over 2 hours, and then he would go back over and point at each individual and repeat, verbatim, their question to him.  I know I couldn't do that.  Why?  Because when I have to remember something I write it on a post-it note or calendar.  He says that he has a stellar memory because he doesn't have post-it notes or calendars.  This was the same way back then.  People didn't own copies of the Old Testament, and yet there were SCORES of people who could recite the entire document from memory from reading the one copy that temples normally had.  Memory was huge in these times, and the chances of people forgetting to add part of the translation (uniformally, I might add, as the copies in existance with historical dates before 400 AD are more or less flawless in consistancy) is pretty much nil.<br>
<br>
A lot of the Gospels came from the Q, which is a written record of everything Christ said.  This hasn't been located yet to my knowledge, but it was very common in these times to keep a written record of what people others thought were important said.  While it was acceptable in rewriting stories to change how someone said something, it was very much not acceptable to change the content of what was said.<br>
<br>
And 4 million copies of a Stephen King Book in existance doesn't make what he said true for a few reasons - first, it's fiction.  If you want to argue that 4 million copies of a Stephen King book prove that Stephen King existed and did create that story, I agree.  That is what I argue that the 24000 historical copies of the bible present.  Plus, you have these found in different cultures and different languages (including ethiopic) with the same core meaning and very few changes in consistancy or even exact wording.  This shows that the translations were all fairly accurate from the origional text.<br>
<br>
